Diabetes Data

JMC

2023-04-28

The following data is from a 652 patient cohort who received consecutive care for 5 years. Values are from time of diagnosis until five years after first diagnosis of diabetes.

Regression for Patients

Change in A1c Calculated (Last A1c in CY - First A1c in CY) - Therefore, negative number suggest improvement (i.e. Final A1c=5% - Starting A1c=6% = -1%)

Data frame used is grouped by patients. (652 individuals)

It doesn’t make sense in this data parameter to examine presence/absence of A1c greater than 8 or 9 because most/all patients wil have had one at some point in the 5 year timeframe.

Regression for Patients by Calendar Year (CY)

Data frame used is grouped by patients and year of care. Each patient has 5-6 observations. (3440 observations for 652 individuals)

Regression for All Observations

This uses the dataframe that includes all observations for all patients with 5 years of continuous care (8817 observations for 652 patients)

Mixed effects with patient id as random effect

ICC Calculation for null model hba data (hba ~ 1 (random=~1|patient_id))

## [1] 0.4926933

ICC Calculation (hba~intervention (random=~1|patient_id))

## [1] 0.4952377

Using package “ICC” to calculate ICC -

LowerCI the lower confidence interval limit, where the confidence level is set by alpha

UpperCI the upper confidence interval limit, where the confidence level is set by alpha

N the total number of individuals or groups used in the analysis

k the number of measurements per individual or group. In an unbalanced design, k is always less than the mean number of measurements per individual or group and is calculated using the equation in Lessells and Boag (1987).

varw the within individual or group variance
